{"sections":[],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/customtypes"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"kind":"article","identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/CustomTypes","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"major":0,"patch":0},"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"title":"Using Custom Types","role":"article"},"seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Articles and Tutorials","identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor"],"generated":true}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"Overview","level":2,"text":"Overview","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Creating a subclass of a Godot type involves a few steps:"}]},{"type":"orderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Subclassing an existing Godot type with the usual Swift syntax.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Registering your type with Godot, so users can create instances of it","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and configure it from the user interface."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Augment the type with your own custom behaviors.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Expose your properties, methods and signals to the Godot Editor.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"anchor":"Subclassing-a-Godot-Type","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Subclassing a Godot Type"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To subclass a Godot type, you would follow the usual Swift idiom to subclass,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"and annotate it with the @Godot macro, like this:"}]},{"code":["@Godot","class MySprite: Sprite {","    var timePassed: Double = 0","","    override func _process (delta: Double) {","        time_passed += delta","    ","        var newPos = Vector2(x: Float (10 + (10 * sin(time_passed * 2.0))),","                             y: Float (10.0 + (10.0 * cos(time_passed * 1.5))))","    ","        self.position = newPos","    }","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Godot"},{"text":" macro does a few things, it creates a default constructor that","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"follows the convention to call the parent "},{"code":"init()","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" method and performs any","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"registrations that you might have done in your class for variables or methods.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"As you will see later, the @Godot macro is applied to a class definition, and","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"will scan your type for various other macros to integrate with Godot.   These","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"attributes will not work if you attempt to apply those in a Swift"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"extension-method, as the @Godot macro has no visibility into those."}]},{"level":2,"text":"Register Your Type","anchor":"Register-Your-Type","type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Now we need to tell Godot about the existence of your type, to do this you need"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to call the ","type":"text"},{"code":"register(type:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" method.   I like to register all my types at","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"startup, but you can do this at any time after the module has been initialized.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Your module gets initialized on a callback from Godot at different stages, this"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"is how I register my types:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["\/\/\/ This method will be invoked at different stages of the execution,","\/\/\/ in our example, we register the type when the level being used is","\/\/\/ `.scene`.","","func setupScene (level: GDExtension.InitializationLevel) {","    if level == .scene {","        register(type: SwiftSprite.self)","    }","}","","\/\/\/ This is the entry point referenced from the `.gdextension` file","\/\/\/ that you used to declare the Swift extension:","@_cdecl (\"swift_entry_point\")","public func swift_entry_point(","    interfacePtr: OpaquePointer?,","    libraryPtr: OpaquePointer?,","    extensionPtr: OpaquePointer?) -> UInt8","{","    print (\"SwiftSprite: Starting up\")","    guard let interfacePtr, let libraryPtr, let extensionPtr else {","        return 0","    }","    initializeSwiftModule(interfacePtr, libraryPtr, extensionPtr, initHook: setupScene, deInitHook: { x in })","    return 1","}"]},{"text":"Defining your class behavior","level":2,"anchor":"Defining-your-class-behavior","type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To make your custom type interesting, you will want to alter the default","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"behavior that Godot provides.   In Godot, this is achieved by overwriting one or","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"more of the virtual methods available in a class.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In Godot, methods that can be overwritten start with an underscore, like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"_ready","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" for example."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"While this would not have been my choice desining the API, I find that there is","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"enough external documentation in the Godot  world, that I decided to stick to","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"it."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In the example shown above, we overwrote the method ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"_process"},{"type":"text","text":" which is invoked"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"continously by Godot and we use it to change the position of our sprite."}]},{"text":"Surfacing Methods, Properties and Signals","level":2,"type":"heading","anchor":"Surfacing-Methods-Properties-and-Signals"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In addition to modifying the behavior of a built-in type, you might want to","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"surface properties that would allow users to customize your type from the Godot"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"editor, or expose methods that can be invoked by users from either other"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"programming languages, like GDScript or C#, and you might want to surface","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" that your object emits that can be wired up externally."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To do this, you will be using the "},{"code":"@Godot","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro to annotate your class, like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"this:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["@Godot","class SwiftSprite: Sprite2D {","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"When you use the "},{"code":"@Godot","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro, a number of additional macros can be used inside"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"your class, like ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"#signal"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"Signals.md","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":", ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Callable"},{"type":"text","text":" to surface a method to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Godot, and ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Export"},{"text":" to ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"Exports.md","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Behind the scenes these macros use the lower-level "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ClassDB","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" API to define functions,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"properties and their values.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Overriding Methods","level":2,"anchor":"Overriding-Methods"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Godot Object model does not surface a traditional object-oriented system."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"Not all the methods surfaced by the Godot API can be overwritten.  The"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"SwiftGodot binding makes this explicit.   Methods that can be overwritten are"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"declared as "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"open"},{"text":", while those that can not be overwritten are declared as","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"public"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Godot prefixes all of the overwritable methods with an underscore (we have seen"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"in this guide some examples already, like "},{"code":"_process","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":").","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Another important difference is that Godot does not expect your code to call the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"“super” method, in fact, those methods do nothing in SwiftGodot."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Of course, if your Swift code relies on a class hierarhcy where you do delegate"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"code to the original implementation, you should still call the base class"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"method.   For example:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["@Godot ","class Base: Node2D {","    override func _ready () { ","        \/* important work *\/ ","        \/* no need to call super._ready *\/","    }","}","","class Derived: Base {","    override func _ready () {","        \/* some prep work here *\/","        \/* because we want to execute the Base._ready important work *\/","        super._ready ()","        \/* some additional work here *\/","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can think of those methods that can be overwritten as hooks into Godot, but"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with an important distinction.   When you override those methods, Godot knows"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"that you overwrote them, and might take a different course of action based on it.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Surfacing Methods","type":"heading","anchor":"Surfacing-Methods","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To surface a method, apply the ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Callable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" attribute to it, this will register"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the method with Godot.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The only limitation is that the parameters of those methods need to be one"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"of the types that Godot can surface to the rest of the engine: anything that can","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"be passed in a "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variant","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["@Callable","func readyCallback (text: String) {","    print (\"readyCallback method called with value: \\(text)\")","    return nil","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Now your method can be invoked from the Godot editor or from scripts written in other languages."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The functions can be any of the types that can be wrapped in a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"Variant.md"},{"text":" including the core Swift data types for integers and","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"floats, the Godot Object subclasses as well as ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantCollection","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" and"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ObjectCollection","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Callable"},{"type":"text","text":" macro only works in your class definition, and will not work"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"on Swift class extensions."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":3,"text":"Surfacing Properties and Variables","type":"heading","anchor":"Surfacing-Properties-and-Variables"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To surface properties and variables, use the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Export","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" attribute on them.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The simplest use case works like this:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["@Godot","class Demo: Node3D {","    @Export var greeting: String = 0","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The above code surfaces a property called ","type":"text"},{"code":"greeting","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to Godot of the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"type string.  Strings and numbers can be edited in many interesting"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"ways in the Godot editor, and that is exposed via two optional parameters"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Export"},{"type":"text","text":" attribute: a "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropertyHint","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" and sometimes those hints","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"can take an optional string with additional confirmation information."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To learn more, read the "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports"},{"text":" page.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Signals","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Signals"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Surfacing signals is covered in the "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" document."}]},{"text":"Low-Leve Details: PropInfo","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Low-Leve-Details-PropInfo"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"In SwiftGodot, the ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" structure is used to define argument types,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"properties and return values.  You will be exposed to these when you define","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"signal parameters.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This is only required if you do not use the various macros provided by"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"SwiftGodot."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"It looks like this:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let textArgument =  PropInfo(","    propertyType: .string,","    propertyName: StringName (\"myArg\"),","    className: \"SwiftSprite\",","    hint: .typeString,","    hintStr: \"\", ","    usage: .default)"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In this case, we are declaring a property of the Godot type string, and we call","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"this ","type":"text"},{"code":"myArg","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":".  The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"className"},{"text":" is the name of the class that we are defining it,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"and we can provide additional hints as to how this might be used (The Godot","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"editor can provide custom UI Editors based on this information)."}]}]}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"You will typically extend the functionality of your Godot game by creating"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"classes that derive from one of the various Godot types and adjust the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"behavior accordingly."}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"references":{"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/VariantCollection":{"kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"VariantCollection"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"VariantCollection","kind":"identifier"}],"role":"symbol","title":"VariantCollection","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantCollection","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variantcollection","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This represents a typed array of one of the built-in types from Godot"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/RunningInEditor":{"type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"There are cases where you might want some of your Swift code for your extension"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to run while it is being used in the Godot Editor.","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor","role":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/runningineditor","kind":"article","title":"Running Code in the Godot Editor"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Exports":{"role":"article","kind":"article","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"In Godot, class members can be exported. This means their value gets saved along"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with the resource (such as the scene) they’re attached to. They will also be"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"available for editing in the property editor. Exporting is done by using the","type":"text"}],"title":"Exports","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/exports"},"Variant.md":{"url":"Variant.md","title":"Variant","identifier":"Variant.md","type":"link","titleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Variant"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/ClassDB":{"type":"topic","kind":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"ClassDB"}],"role":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"ClassDB"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A class information repository."}],"title":"ClassDB","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ClassDB","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/classdb"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Differences":{"role":"article","kind":"article","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This document lists some common differences between GDSscript and SwiftGodot."}],"title":"SwiftGodot API differences to GDScript","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/differences"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Signals":{"role":"article","kind":"article","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","abstract":[{"text":"Signals in Godot are used by objects to post interesting events that are","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"taking place, and can be used by users to easily add behavior and react"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to changes."}],"title":"Signals","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/signals"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/PropertyHint":{"fragments":[{"text":"enum","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PropertyHint","kind":"identifier"}],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/propertyhint","kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","title":"PropertyHint","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropertyHint","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"PropertyHint","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[],"type":"topic"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/PropInfo":{"type":"topic","abstract":[{"text":"PropInfo structures describe arguments to signals, and methods as well as return values from methods.","type":"text"}],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/propinfo","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","role":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PropInfo","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"PropInfo","kind":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"PropInfo"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Framework to write Godot Game Extensions using the Swift Programming Language."}],"title":"SwiftGodot","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot","role":"collection","type":"topic"},"Signals.md":{"titleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"to define signals"}],"url":"Signals.md","title":"to define signals","identifier":"Signals.md","type":"link"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variants":{"role":"article","kind":"article","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Follow up on the fundamental building block of Godot’s data types."}],"title":"Variants","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variants"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/ObjectCollection":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This represents a typed array of one of the built-in types from Godot"}],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ObjectCollection","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"ObjectCollection","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"ObjectCollection","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"ObjectCollection"}],"kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/objectcollection"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variant":{"kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"Variant"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"Variant"}],"title":"Variant","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Variant objects box various Godot Objects, you create them with one of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"constructors, and you can retrieve the contents using the various extension","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"constructors that are declared on the various types that are wrapped.","type":"text"}],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variant","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variant"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/BindingNodes":{"role":"article","kind":"article","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes","abstract":[{"text":"You will find yourself referencing nodes from a scene in your code.   In","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"GDScript, that is usually achieved by using the dollar sign and the name of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"object you want to reference."}],"title":"Referencing Nodes from your Scene","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/bindingnodes"},"Exports.md":{"type":"link","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"surface properties","type":"text"}],"title":"surface properties","url":"Exports.md","identifier":"Exports.md"}}}